\begin{block}{INTRODUCTION}
\emph{Scattering of light} is the phenomenon in which light rays get deviated from its straight path on striking an obstacle like dust or gas molecules, water vapours etc. present in the atmosphere.
\\Principal forms of scattering are as follows:\bigskip
\\ \emph{1.Rayleigh Scattering: }
\\ \emph{Raleigh} is elastic scattering from small particles such as atoms or molecules, resulting in scattered radiation that occurs in all directions uniformly. It is wavelength dependent with shorter wavelengths being more scattered.\bigskip 
\\ \emph{2.Debye or Mie Scattering: }
\\ \emph{Debye or Mie} is an elastic scattering mechanism which occurs from relatively large particles or molecules with dimensions comparable with the wavelength of the incident radiation, or larger. The effect is not very wavelength dependent.\bigskip
\\ \emph{3.Raman Scattering: }
\\ \emph{Raman} is an inelastic scattering mechanism where the frequency of the scattered radiation is changed by the gain or loss of energy which corresponds to energy levels in an atom or molecule. It is very weak and is typically much smaller than the Rayleigh scattered light.\bigskip
\\ \emph{5.Thompson Scattering: }
\\ \emph{Thompson scattering} is an elastic scattering mechanism where light is scattered by charged particles. A comparable form of scattering called \emph{Compton scattering} is an inelastic form of Thompson scattering which occurs when the energy of the incident radiation starts to become comparable to the rest energy of the charged particle. 


\end{block}



%----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%	INTRODUCTION
%----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------



\begin{alertblock}{FACT BOX}
Dr.C V Raman recieved the Nobel Prize in Physics in the year 1930 for his groundbreaking theory in the field of $scattering$ and hence for the dicovery of $Raman$ $Scattering.$
\end{alertblock}

\end{column} % End of the first column

