\begin{block}{WHY IS OUR SKY BLUE ?}
Let us consider atmospheric particles like gas molecules/dust particles etc. ,i.e, the obstacle for scattering to be roughly spherical with radius 'r' and the wavelength of the incident radiation be  {\lambda}.\bigskip
\\ Hereby, we can define dimensionless 'size parameter', x = 2\pi r/\lambda.\bigskip
\\ Particles with x too much less than 1 are relatively ineffective at scattering radiation. Within this so-called \emph{Rayleigh scattering regime} the expression for the $scattering$ $efficiency$ is of the form K \propto \lambda ^{-4} .\bigskip
\\Now, if we compare the scattering efficiency of blue light with red lights(wavelength 0.47 and 0.64 micrometers respectively) we get:\\ K(blue)/K(red) = {(0.64/0.47)}^{4}=3.45.\bigskip \bigskip
\\ \emph{This explains the predominance of blue light in the sky over any other colour in the visible spectrum, as scattering efficiency of blue radiation is more than that of other radiations}   




\end{block}
%------------------------------------------------


\begin{figure}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{blue.jpg}
\caption{ predominance of blue in the sky}
\end{figure}

\begin{block}{COLOR OF THE SUN DURING SUNRISE AND SUNSET}
The sky and the Sun at sunset or sunrise appears red. Near the horizon, most of the blue light and shorter wavelengths are scattered away. Thus, the light that reaches our eyes is of longer wavelengths. This results to the reddish shade of the Sun.\bigskip
\\ The scattering here has certainly occurred due to obstacles like molecules of light gases such as Helium, Hydrogen etc.




\end{block}


